strategy: The first data point I would look at is the quality of the kitchen, because I've had terrible kitchens before and that's a deal breaker for me. Anything "very bad" was immediately off the table. The next most important factor was the size of the yard. With two working breed dogs, I would prefer a decently sized yard. From there, traffic and noise pollution, again because of the dogs. I have no children so schools didn't play a role for me. Things like A/C and access to parks were also relevant, assuming the other needs/desires were met.
strategy2:
I think my description pretty well covered it. 
I had a focus/emphasis on one key feature, with another feature as a very close second.
There were a few other features that definitely factored, especially when the deciding "very bad" kitchen was not in play, and although they may have been more minimal compared to the features that mattered most to me, at times they were significant enough (such as reasonably comparable kitchens and yards, but significantly less noise pollution) that they made the difference in my decision.
metastrategy: As requested, I paid attention to what was dictating my choices in section 1. Going through section 1 imagining I was really making these choices for a home for myself helped me remain consistent in my choices, instead of just abstractly trying to decide which home was "better" objectively versus what I would consider better for myself.

strategy: By far the most important factor for me was the quality of the heat and AC units. I refuse to settle for anything less than moderate on those, so the choice was made very easy for me on many trials. There were some that were either moderate or very good where I was willing to compromise. The two other factors I looked at in these situations were the size of the house and kitchen quality. If there was a substantial difference in the size then I may be swayed, and if a kitchen was very bad I would want to for sure avoid it if the AC was negligible to me. Most of the other factors were nice, but not something to greatly influence me. For instance, I have no kids so the nearby school quality did not really matter to me. Things like being close to a park were nice, but did not influence me like the other 3 factors did.
strategy2: I used one piece of information, the heat/AC quality, as the most important factor. I weighed that one a lot and a couple others, the size of the house and kitchen quality, a little bit. All other factors were ignored for the most part.
metastrategy: I focused in on AC/heat quality right away and did not really stray away from it. I was very aware of how I was making my choices. I believe there was only a single trial where I chose a house with worse quality.

strategy: Between homes, I mostly really prioritized size and convenience. And by the latter I for the most part mean AC. As someone who lives in a place with freezing winters and scorching summers, its unthinkable for me to live in a place with poor temperature management. I also preferred larger houses for obvious reasons, after all if I'm paying I might as well try to rent the biggest home I can afford. Another key factor is the house's age. I don't want a home thats worn and torn, or not up to modern safety standards. Although its easy to imagine an old house having an alluring history, for me thats not going to seal any deal. Things such as local schools, traffic, noise, etc all are important but not priorities for me.
strategy2: My strategy now has more or less remained the same. Focus on building age, size, and temperature control, whilst other factors are important but not nearly as so as before. My priority still of course remains being temperature control. I also put more stock into traits I can control. Even if a kitchen is low quality, with some renovations, I could potentially change that. I can't however change traffic control.
metastrategy: My choice process was simply based off what I prioritized. I can't equally choose value for each attribute so I choose two or three that I would prioritize the most, and then have varying levels of low value for the rest of the qualities.

strategy: I always chose the home with the best school district since I have children to worry about. You can also tell a lot about a neighborhood based on the school district. In most cases, neighborhoods with good school districts tend to be safer. Small homes don't bother me much, I know how to fit a family in a small space. Small homes are much less expensive to run also, so I didn't look much at size. Bad heating and air conditioning can be fixed with portable heaters, portable air conditioners, and fans. Portable heating and air conditioning is also much cheaper because you can heat or cool room by room. So called bad kitchens can usually be fixed with a coat of paint, and a good scrubbing. Other things like noise pollution and traffic don't really bother me much. My family is already noisy, so noise pollution is like white noise to me. Small lot size doesn't bother me, less upkeep. So in the end, the best school district was the deciding factor.
strategy2: I would still make all of my decisions based on the quality of the school. Everything else is trivial. Like I said in the other writing part of this study. I can fix the heating and ac problems with portable units. Bad kitchens usually need a good cleaning. Small spaces are livable with organizational skills. Noise pollution and traffic is easy to ignore. Of course I would prefer the perfect home with a big lot, close to parks, lots of square footage, good schools, good kitchen, good heating and cooling. However, I am not made out of money and can't afford to be picky when I have to worry about sending my kids to a decent school.
metastrategy: I know what my choice process was because my decision was consistent the entire way through. It was always based on the best school.

strategy: When it came to the data points provided, the main ones that influenced my decision were the quality of climate control, total area of the plot (house+yard) and the quality of the kitchen. I used noise pollution and school quality (which I used as a measure of the quality of the neighborhood) as tie breakers. I didn't find myself caring about the distance to parks, traffic, or house age as much. To start I usually checked the appliance and climate quality, then if those are close to even, I checked the total area of the two houses (preferring houses of at least 800 sq ft) then checked the yard size, if the yard was big enough, I usually counted it as a pro even if the house had a bad kitchen, because I could grow and cook food outside.
strategy2: I'd say my description of how I made choices was pretty well described by the strategies presented in Section 2. I wouldn't change how I described my strategy.
metastrategy: I knew how to answer the questions in section 2 easily because I went through the same mental process every time I made a decision in section 1, where I evaluated the features that mattered the most first, then the ones that mattered a lot, then used the features that I cared about a little to break any ties if the two homes were close.

He checked which home was better on each feature (i.e. which home 'won' on each feature), and chose the home that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
strategy: I don't have kids, so I ignored the school ratings. I'm single and don't have much stuff, so house size meant nothing to me either (as long as it was over 650 sq/ft). and I don't care when a house was built - I'm just renting not buying. I do have dogs, so if a house had 0 yard that choice was eliminated. After that I thought about which factors would impact me the most/most often. To me those were noise and traffic. I hate driving (and am a nervous driver on the rare occasions I do drive) so low - moderate traffic was a priority. And I like to spend time outside, and like quiet at night. So noise pollution would be pretty much a constant bother for me, and sow low- moderate noise was a big factor. Overall "outside" elements weighed more heavily  - noise, traffic, yard size, distance to park. The one combo that altered that was very bad kitchen and very bad HVAC. I didn't like picking a house that had the lowest rating for both of those, as it seemed like those combined might make for a bad indoor experience. Kitchen was more important than HVAC as kitchen would be a daily thing, whereas in my experience HVAC only comes into play about 6-7 months a year. But overall it was a gestalt - enough good things that were really good could outweigh almost any of the moderate good factors. Except 0 yard - no yard was a no go.
strategy2: I would say it mostly stays the same. But I might emphasize more how the gestalt was pretty important, but a bit fluid depending on how good my most preferred factors were rated and how poorly the other factors were. Sometimes the combo could end up meaning that I picked the house with the lowest possible rating for my most important factors (noise and traffic) if everything else was perfect. And I might mention that I didn't always thinks of each rating on the rating scale separately. For example in most cases "moderate": was good enough, so anything moderate and above (or below if we are talking negative factors like noise and traffic) weighed about the same. Unless I needed a "tie-breaker",
metastrategy: Because I consciously thought about my choices when I made them, and mentally figured out why I was doing what I was doing as I made the choices. I tend to analyze my actions anyway, so I was predisposed to think about what my choice process was.
meditation_exp6: I am relatively new to mindfulness meditation.

permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback: I'm not sure if it took the stated amount of time as I am in fullscreen and can't see my computer clock, lol. One thing - you asked about mindfulness practice at the end, and I answered yes as I have tried it before, as part of therapy. But your followup questions didn't really apply - I only tried it twice, it triggered panic attacks both times (my body associates controlled breathing with panic attacks and starts one if I do that process) and irrational rage and frustration. It is not for me, and it has been close to 10 years since those sessions.

strategy: Primarily, I looked at the Heat/AC system information, since this is a really important factor not only in comfort but in the ongoing costs of housing. I also looked at Noise Pollution, since this could affect quality of life, though I did not consider it more important than heat/AC. The other factors I did not consider particularly important, or at least not important enough to outrank the two other factors.
strategy2: Yes, I guess I would be more specific. At first, I looked at multiple factors, including Quality of Heat/AC System, Noise Pollution, Traffic, and School System Reputation and tried to extrapolate what this location might be like. For example, an area with a low School System Reputation may also have a high poverty rate and have less access to grocery stores and things like that; an area with high Noise Pollution but low Traffic scores likely indicates industrial noise, such as nearby factories, an airport, train tracks. However, I then realized I don't care that much about school systems and there are too many factors involved in school rankings and also that noise pollution is a modifiable problem â€” in fact at this very moment, I live in a very small apartment right over a busy road with much commerce and loud noises all day and night, but it doesn't bother me because high quality ear plugs exist. AC/Heating systems on the other hand are expensive, difficult, and (for renters) maybe even impossible to alter and have a huge impact on quality of life. So after the first few trials, I realized that was the most important, non-modifiable quality that I actually cared about.
metastrategy: I explicitly thought it out. It wasn't, like, instinctual or something. For the first 10 or so trials (maybe even the practice trials), I looked at all the different variables and tried to weigh what I'd do in real life, then I made some decisions and mostly stuck with them for the rest of the choices.

strategy:
1)  I first looked at the quality of the HVAC System.  Nothing worse than a furnace going out in the middle of winter or an air conditioner not working in the heat of summer.  It can take 3 days to a week or longer to replace a HVAC System. So, that was my first priority. 

2)  My next consideration was the kitchen.  If the HVAC is good, but the kitchen is bad, I feel I can do quite a bit to get the kitchen looking and functioning better to my needs.  

3)  Size of home was a consideration, but not a priority.  It is just my husband and I so we can go with a smaller home if the HVAC system is good.

4) The noise level is a slight consideration, but we can also play music or keep TV on to get around this.

5)  The year of the home is a slight consideration, however, we are only renting.  I would be much more concerned if we were buying.

6)  The yard size does not matter much to us.  We are gone quite a bit from home.  A yard is nice, but not critical, as we do not have children living at home, and we do not entertain much.

7)  Schools and rating of education does not matter to us as our children are grown and do not live at home.

8)  Living near a park is nice, but since our children are not living at home we most likely would not use the park, so it does not matter how close or far it is.
strategy2: No, I still have the same strategy as I wrote about before.  My number one concern was the HVAC System, but it was not exactly strategy E (only 1 single feature considered) as I did want a nice kitchen but willing to settle if HVAC System good.  I did look over and consider all the other features, but I prioritized which were my main concerns. The other features were "what can we live with" in my mind if I got the features I most wanted but if a feature was bigger, I did take into consideration exactly how much bigger.
metastrategy: When looking over the various strategies A, B, C, D. E and F I could tell my thought processes easily.  I had a priority, like strategy E, but I also cared about another feature, as in strategy F.  I knew I cared a different amount on each one, so I did not use strategy A, but did use strategy B. I did care about size of home (but only second to the HVAC System) but if the feature was bigger I did care about how much bigger, strategy D and not strategy C.

strategy: I always started with the Heat/AC as these are life or death things that must work. ALso, they often break at temp extremems, and it can be hard to get them fixed quickly. If there was a big difference, the die was cast pretty much immediately. If they were close, then the kitchen was second for me, as a retired senior on a fixed income I have to cook at home (plus with Covid I'm not a fan of going to restuarants.) Since it's just me, schools and even sizes didn't really matter. I do like to walk, so Parks could matter, but I don't recall ever getting to that as a decision point. I would prefer newer buildings in general as less likely of something breaking unless it was just remodeled, but again, I never got to that point.
strategy2: No change. Heat/AC predominated, with kitchen a distant second. I don't think I ever got past these two as I looked at the differences in that order, and in the examples you gave, the difference in those first 2 was often stark and made the choice very easy and also very fast.  I didn't like taking a bad kitchen, but for a very good heat/AC I would live with it. There was a few examples of that.
metastrategy: I'm a computer programmer! So I had a "procedure" for making my choices (or a decision tree if you will.) I was also a computer chess programmer, and a key part of that is the evaluation function that wraps together a number of factors based on the factor score and then the factor importance. So I've been doing this type of thing for a very long time and it felt very natural and "intuitive" at this stage of my life.

It seemed that the trade-off was usually a moderate to good kitchen meant the heating and 
AC was bad, and that was not fun. But, I figured I could always use portable electric heaters in the winter and big fans in the summer, as that would be worth it to not have a gross kitchen. I think every now and then I chose to go with better heating/AC, but most of the time it was the kitchen that was the deal breaker. I was also keeping in mind that since this was a rental, I could move after a year and would only have to tolerate those conditions for a relatively short amount of time.

strategy: One of my greatest priorities was selecting the home near the school with the better reputation. While I do not have children, I believe that school reputation is a good proxy for overall area quality and safety. I also prioritized AC/Heating Unit condition because I live in an area where the summers get very hot and the winters get very cold. If I can not rely on heating and air conditioning, my quality of life will greatly suffer. My third priority was sq ft of the home. Larger homes, especially if they were significantly larger, were more valuable to me. If all three of these factors were strongest in one home, I almost certainly picked that home. If 2 of the 3 factors favored one home, I typically selected that home, unless the differences were not great (ie a 200 sq ft difference in space). If I felt that the houses were relatively even in these three factors, I looked at other indicators. Lower commuting times to the park was favorable. I always preferred newer homes, especially if the difference was greater than approximately 40 years. I also occasionally looked at kitchen quality as a final separator. I rarely considered noise level or traffic level, because I am a heavy sleeper so noise does not bother me, and I do not have to commute to work.
strategy2: My description of my strategy has not changed at all. My primary deciding factors were reputation of local schools, AC/Heating Unit Condition, and size of home. If weighing these 3 factors did not produce a clearly better option, I also considered distance to parks, age of home, kitchen quality, and yard size.
metastrategy: I was very conscious of my choice process throughout the entirety of Section 1. I was weighing options in my head for each of the 100 trials and developed a fairly consistent process throughout.

The second most important factor was noise pollution. It drove me crazy. So my next criteria was Noise Pollution. I didn't want to live anywhere with high noise pollution, unless the alternative was a house with no yard.

The next most important factor was yard or house size.

The next most important was traffic. I would prefer to live in an area with low traffic.

A/C, kitchen quality and school reputation had no bearing on my answers. I do not have kids so the school doesn't matter, and I feel the A/C and kitchen are things you can fix up after you buy a house.

The closeness to a park didn't really matter either, as even a 30 minute drive isn't too far in my opinion.

She cared about both of those two features an equal amount. To decide which home was better overall, she compared how much better each home was on those two features.
binwts_comp2_description: Person description: When making her choices between homes in Section 2, Monica cared about four features: the size of the home, the size of the yard, the amount of traffic, and the amount of noise pollution. She cared about the size of the home and yard the most, but she also cared a little about the other two features.
binatts_comp1_description: Person description: When making his choices between homes in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: the size of the home, the amount of traffic, and the closeness to parks. He checked which home was better on each feature (i.e. which home 'won' on each feature), and chose the home that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between homes in Section 1, Joe cared about three features: the year the building was built, the closeness to parks, and the size of the yard. He considered the difference between the two homes on each feature (e.g. a 100 sq. ft. yard versus a 400 sq. ft. yard = a 300 sq. ft. difference), and then weighed those differences together to figure out w
strategy:
I first looked to make sure the size of the yard was not "0". Because I have a large dog, and I love gardening, I want to have a yard, even a small one. The second thing I looked at was noise pollution. Loud noises bother me a lot and make me anxious, so I need a home that has no more than moderate noise pollution. The only time I chose a "high" rating for noise pollution was when the other option was to have no yard. The rest of the options I didn't care about nearly as much. I don't have children, so I don't care about school quality. I don't care much about what year the home was built. It is only my partner and me, so a smaller house is fine. Nearness to parks is nice, but I can drive to one if there is not one within walking distance. A decent kitchen is nice, but I have often made do with a not-so-nice one, so it is low down the list. 

As for the AC/heat, I placed a low priority on it assuming the hypothetical rental was in the PNW, where I live now. If I was to rent somewhere like the South, where it is exceptionally humid in the summer, or the desert Southwest, where it is well over 100 degrees for several months a year, I would definitely place a much higher priority on having a good AC system. If I lived somewhere that it was regularly below 0 all winter, a good heating system would be a priority.
strategy2: My strategy description is the same as it was previously.
metastrategy: My choice process was based on two specific home characteristics (noise pollution and having a yard of any size), though I didn't care about the amount of difference between the two homes.
meditation_exp6: I am relatively new to mindfulness meditation.
attention_check: I will complete this study with my full attention.
permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback:
The last fill-in question was a bit confusing. I hope I answered it correctly. 
I am not sure if it took as long as predicted. It didn't seem to take all that long, but I wasn't paying attention to time.

strategy: I thought about my fondness for the character of older homes and considered the trade-offs I was willing or able to make.  I also considered the collective aspect (more desired features added together could balance out one glaring negative).  I also considered how important or not important some features were, with reference to my needs at this stage of my life.  For example, I don't have children/grandchildren to raise concerns about school quality from an educational standpoint.  However, schools with a bad reputation might also contribute to a population segment prone to vandalism, drug-dealing, theft, and other negative activities that could effect the neighborhood. A decent kitchen took precedence over a heating/AC system.....I can't improve on a very bad kitchen but I can make do with bundling up in cold weather or auxiliary fans in the heat (and save money at the same time).  Noise pollution is relative.....if near an airport, fire station, police station, freeway, etc....I grow accustomed to the sounds and eventually tune them out. I enjoy gardening but if renting, would not want to invest time and money creating a garden spot for someone else's property.
strategy2: I would stick to my concept of considering all the features on a collective basis.
metastrategy: It just seemed intuitive.

strategy: The technique I used was the process of elimination. Meaning, first, I looked at the features that were dealbreakers and I eliminated those. The two dealbreakers were: a home that was about 900 square feet and under, and a home without any yard space. There were some instances when I overlooked the size of the home though, such as when the larger home didn't have a yard, along with the combination of a bad kitchen and A/C and Heating System. I also looked at the age of the home, and with that combo, I was able to make my choice. Every now and then, I would decide the home was too old if it didn't have desirable features. As far as the other features, for myself, a good school nearby is irrelevant. Noise pollution is something I would prefer not to have, but I paid much less attention to that one. Same with the distance to the park. However, I did sometimes consider the level of traffic if I couldn't make a proper decision. I obviously prefer the least amount of traffic, but it's not a dealbreaker. Sometimes there would be a cluster of great features that I couldn't pass up, like a huge yard. Not all of my choices were created equal, but this was the technique I tried to follow as much as I could. Every once and I while, when I couldn't decide, I would go with my gut instinct.
strategy2: My strategy would not have changed at all. I would have still used the process of elimination to eliminate the features that are least desirable, then I would compare them to each home. If there are dealbreakers, like a home that was too small or a home with no yard, then I would compare them to features such as kitchen quality, A/C and Heater quality, and the age of the house. Light traffic and low noise pollution are good, but of two, I preferred light traffic. Closeness to parks isn't a big feature I care about, but it's a bonus. School rating is irrelevant. But unless the home doesn't have a yard, the size is a big deal for me. I've lived in a 700 square feet apartment and it was awful, so that has shaped my opinion. If I had to add any other unmentioned feature that is important, I would say bathroom quality, along with size and possibly the number of bathrooms are something I would have taken into consideration, if they were offered on the list. Anyway though, like I said, I wouldn't change my technique.
metastrategy: I answered them by looking at the provided information that I read. I read the different strategies, thought about it, and then answered the way the questions asked. The process was quite simple and straightforward. If I had doubts about my answer, I would go with my gut instinct.

strategy: I live on the Canadian border.  I've seen it get to 50 below here.  Additionally, I moved here from south Florida because I cannot stand the heat.  So, for me, any HVAC rating of bad or very bad was an automatic disqualifier.  The vast majority of your choices had one house with one of those two ratings compared to a house with a moderate or higher rating, so the better rated house won.  If both houses had systems of moderate or better, (or equally bad ratings) then my next consideration was the kitchen.  I am disabled and housebound, so I don't really care about traffic or how close the park is or the yard size.  I do like to cook.  So, all other things being relatively equal, I chose the house with the better (moderate or higher) kitchen.  For the few remaining houses where both those factors were relatively equal, I looked at the size, (larger being better) and the year built, (newer being better.)  I didn't really need to look at any of the other factors.

strategy:
My number one determining factor is the good reputation of the nearby school. If one column said bad or very bad school, I don't need to consider anything else. Bad schools are a sign of a poor neighborhood with less services and sadly, more crime and unkempt homes. Every realtor I've ever worked with says schools are one of the most sought after location factors for potential buyers. I don't care about square footage because, or poor quality of the kitchen or size of yard. You can renovate and add an addition. If I live in the city, maybe I don't want a yard to maintain, and high noise levels are part of the charm of city life. 
When the schools were rated moderate to very good, then I considered proximity to parks and size of home.
strategy2: In searching for a home, buyers will have to compromise between what they want and what's available and what they can afford. I go into it based on looking for the best house in the neighborhood with the best nearby schools. I will stick by that unless I have the dream option of multiple choices of homes near more than one good school. That's where people want to live, and resale values are most likely higher in these neighborhoods. I am fortunate that I can afford to renovate and put in new kitchens or HVAC systems, so I do have an advantage when looking for a home.
metastrategy: As I said before, I based my decision on one factor. I didn't worry about all the others or what my process was. It wasn't about the process to me.

strategy: The first things I looked at were the kitchen and a/c because they are so expensive and a hassle to fix. I thought the a/c would be easier to fix than the kitchen so I prioritized a good kitchen. The school didn't matter because we homeschool. The year it was built did not factor in either. I found I often had to accept a lot of traffic or noise pollution in order to get something else I wanted, like a bigger house or a nicer kitchen. The yard size was not very important, I'd prefer a smaller yard or no yard anyway. I accepted a smaller house if the kitchen and a/c were okay and the noise pollution was lower. The distance to parks was often not ideal and got ignored in favor of more important things.
strategy2: The kitchen was the biggest factor in determining my choice. I also cared about the a/c, noise pollution, traffic, house size, yard size, and closeness to parks. I didn't really care about the schools or the year the house was built.
metastrategy: I had a strategy and priorities, so it was easy to remember that and answer the questions.
meditation_exp6: I am relatively new to mindfulness meditation.

strategy: My first look was at the size (square feet) of the place, when the difference was double it was difficult to pick the small place.  I am 67 years old so the school system played almost no role in my decision.  After size, I looked at heating/AC condition and kitchen evaluation.  Of minor influence was distance the park, outdoor size and age of place.
strategy2: I think F was the best description of my strategy.  I first looked at the size of the home and the difference between the size of A and B (the larger the difference the harder it was for me to pick the small home - it would need all other factors like AC/Heat, Kitchen and traffic to be very bad).  I looked at multiple items on each and tried to balance size versus the other factors.  I rarely chose the smaller home but I did when it was close and other factors were in the favor of the small home.
metastrategy: I thought about a factor hierarchy when I saw the options and started answering the questions.  I prioritized certain factors and those drove my decision process.  I tried to be consistent over time.

strategy: Noise pollution was my number one criteria in selecting a rental. On every screen I selected the property with the least amount of noise pollution.  Why?  Because perhaps a landlord will improve a bad kitchen or fix bad heating, but the landlord can't do anything about noise pollution -- planes flying overhead, etc. What is the benefit of a large backyard when the noise outside is unhealthy? The choice was rather simple, even moderate noise pollution is better than high noise in the environment where one sleeps and probably works from home. As for the school system, a bad school system can be mitigated with home schooling or, if affordable, a private school.
strategy2: My strategy has not changed ...  Noise pollution is the most important factor to me.  A moderate amount of noise pollution is preferable to a great amount. I'll agree high traffic can contribute to the noise levels but still other kinds of noise pollution is my top issue.
metastrategy: I knew my choices from Section 1 because at the start I knew my top -- and only major == criteria...noise pollution.

strategy: Okay, more than anything, it was about setting priorities.  I wanted to get that out of the way, early on, if nothing else than to be consistent.  There are a few things that I have a little influence over.  Crappy kitchen?  Hey, I can buy a stove or a new fridge.  Age of house?  I've seen well built houses that were built in 1900, and junk heaps that were built in 2011.  Obviously age can be a consideration, but it isn't necessarily a big deal.  So the main points were house size and yard size.  I can't make more yard space, and expanding house square footage isn't always practical or cheap.  So house and yard size really played a factor.  A 600 sq ft house doesn't leave a lot of room to grow, but I'll give up a little yard space for an 1800 sq ft house.  Everything is a trade off, sure, but those 2 items were my primary concerns.
strategy2: Right.  As I said, it was about prioritizing.  It was about what is most important.  Size of house and size of yard were my primary concerns.  I can handle driving 10 more minutes to get to a park.  I can fix a busted AC unit.  I can't just add more yard, and depending on a lot of factors, I may not be able to add on to the size of the house.  Everything is a trade off, but my general focus was on the yard and house size.
metastrategy: I'm going to try to answer this this way, and hope it's satisfactory.  We all make choices.  We make dozens of choices every day.  That's just how life is.  Those choices almost always involve needs, wants and priorities.  Again, just how life is.  I would prefer a larger house, as opposed to a smaller house.  I'd prefer a larger yard over a smaller yard.  As far as how I know what my section one choice process was...  I've explained my priorities twice now.  It's the same way that, say I was presented with the choice of a chicken sandwich or a burger.  I like chicken, so I'd choose chicken.  I'm really not sure how else to explain this.  I made my choices based on what I prioritized to be the most important features.   Again, your task involved trade offs, just like a real home would, but I tried to consistently select the choices that worked best for me.

He considered the difference between the two homes on each feature (e.g. a 100 sq. ft. yard versus a 400 sq. ft. yard = a 300 sq. ft. difference), and then weighed those differences together to figure out w
strategy:
My theory is that if the schools are good, it's probably a decent, safe neighborhood, so that was always the first thing I checked. I don't have children myself, but I do value living in a neighborhood that makes education a priority. 

Next, I looked at the HVAC and kitchen quality. Of course, it's great if both are in good condition, but these weren't ideal houses so I was willing to sacrifice the quality of one of them. But not both - that would be too miserable. I slightly prefer good HVAC over a good kitchen, because I can cope with a bad kitchen, but I hate being too hot or too cold. New kitchens are nice but not essential.

Yard size is important to me, but all yards listed were much too small for my dog, so it didn't matter much to me if the choice was between 200 sq ft and 400 sq ft. (No yard - instant disqualification. Need a bit of space if the dog has to pee in the middle of the night.) Either way, there's just room for some outdoor furniture and a few plants. Small yards mean I'd be walking my dog to the park every day, but to me there's not much difference between a park that's 10 minutes away and one that's 30, because the point is to walk the dog so it's all dog mileage to me.

I live on a major street in an urban area, so I am used to lots of traffic and noise and I know how to cope with both. I'm not afraid of either, so that didn't factor in much.

I can live in 600 square feet, and I can live in 1800. It doesn't make much difference to me, except I wouldn't want a big house with bad HVAC because utilities would be too expensive.
strategy2: Yes, I have a much better understanding of how I processed my choices now. I understand that I preferred some aspects and ignored others. Of my preferred aspects, I weighted them, so that the Quality of Schools was the most important, but I'd give that up for a combination of other aspects that I found appealing. (example: The lure of a very good kitchen AND very good HVAC could have me moving to a neighborhood with bad schools.) If my preferences were bars in a graph, I would be able to combine some to give them more weight and create a longer bar.
metastrategy: After doing a few I got into a rhythm and checked the same things in the same order on every page. I had a mental checklist going and checked off each thing as I went. After doing that 100 times, the checklist was ingrained in my mind so all I had to do was replay it and think about why some of my choices were more important than others.

permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback:
It did take about as long as you said it would. Everything was explained very well and was easy to understand. 
Thanks!

He considered the difference between the two homes on each feature (e.g. a 100 sq. ft. yard versus a 400 sq. ft. yard = a 300 sq. ft. difference), and then weighed those differences together to figure out w
binatts_comp2_description: Person description: When making his choices between homes in Section 1, Xavier cared about three features: the size of the home, the amount of traffic, and the closeness to parks. He checked which home was better on each feature (i.e. which home 'won' on each feature), and chose the home that 'won' on a majority of the three features.
strategy: In deciding between rentals, the most important is the year the home was built.Anything before 1978 has asbestos and lead paint. The newer the better because if I remember correctly there was a phase-in period where old inventory could still be used. If both choices were old homes, then I looked at heating/AC because I would want to be comfortable. Then quality of the kitchen was third most important because I have to cook and try to eat well. These 3 criteria were the most important. School doesn't matter because I have no kids. Yard size doesn't matter. Home size was not important either. Noise and traffic were slightly important but don't figure prominently because the top 3 over-rode them. This study left out other important criteria such as quality and speed of property management, crime level, parking availability, quality of neighbors, distance of police and fire, distance to shopping and work, laundry and gym facilities, and frequency of rent increase. In making decisions, I felt I was often given 2 bad choices to choose from. If this were real life, I would have simply looked for other properties. Not a realistic study.
strategy2: In making decisions, all things are considered at the same time, weighted by importance and circumstances and personal preference. That remains the same. The problem with the design of this  study is that the researcher forced the survey taker to decide on 2 equally bad choices and then asks the survey taker to analyze the decision process as if the decisions were legit. That is researcher interference and invalidates the study. My strategy remained the same, given the restriction given by the scenario and instruction. The instruction even stated, "Also, we specifically want to know how much you cared about each feature while making your decisions in Section 1, NOT how much you care about each feature in real life." That is an admission from the researcher that this study isn't about studying decision making in real life. It's a fantasy study. Waste of funding.
metastrategy: Again, my answers in section 1 was forced by the researcher's methodology, so section 2 was actually invalid. I would have simply rejected many scenario pairs in section 1 in real life, but that was not an option. Don't researchers have to take a course in research methodology anymore?
attention_check: I will complete this study with my full attention.
permission: Yes, I am okay with my answers to these questions
feedback: I've done several of these choose A or B studies. Each had bad choices and researchers forced survey takers to choose one. Don't use this study design anymore. It's flawed because it does not represent the true feelings of the survey taker.

strategy: We once lived in an Apartment with horrible AC, our two small dogs suffered from heatstroke but survived. That can be remedied with some high-powered cooling fans if you have them. I also love to cook and a kitchen is also top on my list. Since this is a rental, it is not permanent so it does not matter the size, neighborhood, etc. I see it as temporary. A lot of traffic does not bother me, hopefully it means there is public transportation available. I have no kids so I don't care about the schools. If the kitchen is bad, it helps to have a larger yard for a grill. Square footage of a rental is not that important.
strategy2: No, rentals are fine unless they are long-term. I am currently renting a much smaller place than I would like, the AC is great, the kitchen is too small and no yard. I know the house I buy will be larger, have a big kitchen and yard for dogs and entertaining, have excellent AC and I do like newer homes. Our schools are all very good but since I have not kids, I don't really care about that. We are living in a tourist town so traffic is always busy but it does not bother me.
metastrategy: I trusted houses with good to excellent AC unless we use a high-powered fan. If the kitchen was excellent, I would have tried for at least moderate AC. If the kitchen was bad, I would have been trying for a yard to grill in. When looking for a house, you make a list of what you want most and what you can live without. Some things are simply better than others.

strategy:
The most important thing to me was the quality of the heat/AC system. If I am not able to be comfortable in the home, not much else about it matters. I tried to avoid bad or very bad heat/AC systems. In the first few choices I might have been more influenced by other things and chosen a bad system, but the more I thought about it, the more I wanted to avoid a bad heat/AC system.

At first I put a lot of importance on the school quality because I thought a bad school might mean a high crime neighborhood. Then the more I thought about it I realized the closest school could be a couple of miles away, so I didn't worry about it as much.

Noise doesn't bother me. Traffic doesn't bother me. The size of the house isn't important. I can deal with a bad kitchen, but a good kitchen would be nice. I prefer a yard, but if there is no yard that's okay. I don't care how far away the park is.
strategy2:
It hasn't changed.

I cared most about the quality of the heat/AC system.

I cared about school reputation and kitchen quality.

I didn't care about other features, but if given a choice, I would prefer little noise, little traffic, bigger yard, bigger house, older house, and closer park.

Nothing was really a deal breaker, but I usually tried to avoid a bad heat/AC system.
metastrategy:
I'm confused about this question. I remember first looking for AC/heat quality. Then I looked at school reputation and kitchen. Then I always looked at everything else even though I knew I would probably go with the best based on heat/AC, school, and kitchen. However, I might have gone with a bad heat/AC if everything else was good. I don't remember for sure.

Even though I would like a good kitchen, I remember choosing a very bad kitchen many times because I wanted the better heat/AC.

strategy: For me--I live alone--the two major determinants are the kitchen and the HVAC system. I can work around everything else. Of the two though, the kitchen is the most important. I can live with a MODERATE kitchen if the HVAC is GOOD or better; I can even work around a VERY BAD HVAC system if the kitchen is MODERATE or better. I don't care about the rating of the HVAC system if the kitchen isn't at least MODERATE. I live in my MODERATE kitchen most of the day. It's where I work and cook, and I'm happy with it. My HVAC system, on the other hand, is BAD.
strategy2: Same as I described it the first time. The quality of the kitchen was paramount. A distant second was the quality of the HVAC system. I could go with a MODERATE kitchen if the HVAC's value was high, but that was as low as I was prepared to go with the kitchen.

strategy: I attached the highest priority to the condition of the kitchen and the Heat/AC. Other factors were considered as well, some (i.e., size of home and yard; traffic and noise) carrying more weight in my decisions than others. I don't have children so school was not a factor. The bottom line: If the condition of the kitchen is lower than "Moderate", that's a deal-breaker for me. A top-notch kitchen is the most important consideration of any home I choose.
strategy2: My strategy was the same as I described previously, for the most part. The explanation might be a little different but the various strategies as they were explained helped me distinguish which methods I practiced in the decision-making process.
metastrategy: I knew when I started how I would decide which home to choose. I know what I like and what features I feel are important (and not important) and applied a certain weight to each feature. As I was reading the different strategies on each page (Strategy A vs. B, et al), I thought about which one I adopted when deciding between options.

strategy: I pretty much based my sole decision on the quality and condition of the AC heat plant. I live in a pretty noisy neighborhood, but I have very low expenses and I have an excellent heating and cooling system. The most expensive thing in what's going to go on in your home besides The rent is going to be the utilities. I'm really good at making do and making bad kitchens look better. I'm a pretty handy person. Can do a certain amount of minimal maintenance and clean up and painting and decorating. So those were the main factors. I don't have pets. I don't have children around, so I don't really need much of a yard. I can manage almost any size of space To live in For rental.
strategy2: No, my strategy is not Changed it all. If I had properties that both had excellent heating and cooling systems, meaning they worked well and they were energy efficient and low cost to operate, then the next thing would probably be size of the house quality of the kitchen Amount of noise And close distance to work. But that would have been the same earlier. It's just I didn't have time to take those things into account. And generally the choices were between not very good and either moderate or very good heating system. So I'm always going to go with the moderate, or very good heating system over a bad or not so good heating system.
metastrategy: It was a very conscious decision on my part.
